{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476397"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:46:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583774"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:28:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:28:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13738"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13738"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0.02,0.84,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60252"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45672"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11809"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60252"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old boy attends a routine health check. He was born at term and has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiac auscultation reveals a grade 4/6 pansystolic murmur, loudest at the left lower sternal border. An echocardiogram demonstrates a small, restrictive ventricular septal defect (VSD).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains why this VSD produces a loud murmur?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Higher pulmonary vascular resistance","Lower velocity of blood flow across the VSD","Larger size of the VSD","Higher pressure gradient across the VSD","Lower left ventricular systolic function"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe loudness of a murmur in a ventricular septal defect (VSD) is inversely related to the size of the defect. In this patient with a small, restrictive VSD, there is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher pressure gradient across the VSD\u003C/strong\u003E, resulting in a higher velocity of blood flow and a louder murmur (grade 4/6).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, a \u003Cstrong\u003Elarger VSD\u003C/strong\u003E would have a lower pressure gradient and velocity of blood flow across the defect, resulting in a softer murmur. The pressure gradient is the key determinant of the loudness of the murmur, rather than the absolute size of the defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigher pulmonary vascular resistance\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease the left-to-right shunt across the VSD and result in a softer murmur. \u003Cstrong\u003ELower velocity of blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E would also result in a softer murmur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELower left ventricular systolic function\u003C/strong\u003E may result in a softer murmur due to reduced cardiac output and flow across the VSD, but this is not the primary determinant of the murmur loudness in an otherwise well child with a small VSD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The loudness of a murmur in a ventricular septal defect (VSD) is inversely related to the size of the defect.","Smaller VSDs have a higher pressure gradient and velocity of blood flow across the defect, resulting in a louder murmur.","Larger VSDs have a lower pressure gradient and velocity of blood flow, resulting in a softer murmur."],"references":["Fulton DR, Saleeb S. Isolated ventricular septal defects (VSDs) in infants and children: Anatomy, clinical features, and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/isolated-ventricular-septal-defects-vsds-in-infants-and-children-anatomy-clinical-features-and-diagnosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45672"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13738"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45672"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-10T13:59:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-10T14:05:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60252"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"